<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910607-0029</DOCNO><DOCID>910607-0029.</DOCID><HL>   Two Investors Settle   SEC Suit Focusing   On Trading in Stocks</HL><DATE>06/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   MHP</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Two California investors settled a Securitiesand Exchange Commission lawsuit accusing them of trading instocks mentioned in advance copies of Business Week.   Stephen R. Rasinski agreed to turn over alleged illegaltrading profits totaling $137,044 and pay a penalty of thesame amount. Mr. Rasinski will actually pay $46,100, whichthe SEC said is the value of his only available assets. TheSEC said it can seek additional payments from Mr. Rasinski ifhis financial condition changes.</LP><TEXT>   Lawrence M. Small agreed to turn over alleged illegaltrading profits of $57,560 and pay the same amount as apenalty. The SEC waived payment of the penalty because of Mr.Small's inability to pay.   In settling the lawsuits, Mr. Rasinski and Mr. Smallneither admitted nor denied the alleged securities-lawviolations, said to have occurred between 1986 and 1988. Eachof the defendants previously pleaded guilty to two counts ofsecurities fraud in a related criminal case.   The SEC alleged that the two men learned the contents ofthe advance copies of Business Week from John L. Petit, aformer stockbroker at Smith Barney, Harris Upham andamp; Co. Mr.Petit obtained the copies from Shayne Walters, who then wasemployed at a plant that prints the magazine for McGraw-HillInc. Mr. Petit and Mr. Walters previously settled SEC suitsin connection with the transactions and pleaded guilty torelated criminal charges.</TEXT></DOC>